---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Pilgrimage">
    <section class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16">
        <h1 class="mb-2 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900">4-Day Pilgrimage Program</h1>
        <p class="mb-2 text-lg leading-8 text-neutral-700">
            <strong>(Optional – before the retreat)</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="mb-10 text-lg leading-8 text-neutral-700">Dates: December 24, 2026 – December 27, 2026</p>

        <div class="grid gap-6 text-neutral-800">
            <section class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold">General Introduction</h2>
                <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    This is an optional journey for practitioners who wish to take time to settle the mind, pay respects at important sacred sites in the life of
                    the Buddha, and prepare inwardly before entering the main retreat.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    According to the actual pilgrimage route of the group, over the course of four days participants will visit sacred places associated with key
                    stages in the life of the Buddha: from the period of ascetic practice, the turning point toward the Middle Way, the place of enlightenment,
                    major sites of teaching, and finally the later landmarks connected with the closing period of his life before Parinirvana.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    For this reason, the pilgrimage is not simply movement from one location to another, but an opportunity for each practitioner to contemplate
                    more deeply the Buddha’s path of practice, awakening, and teaching, while also nurturing reverence, mindfulness, and inner preparation before
                    the retreat begins.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold">4-Day Itinerary</h2>

                <div class="space-y-8">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold">Day 1 – December 24</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4 font-medium text-neutral-800">Dungeshwari – Sujata – Bodh Gaya</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-4 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                            <li>
                                <strong>Dungeshwari Cave</strong><br />
                                The place where the Buddha practiced severe asceticism for many years before realizing that extreme self-mortification does not lead
                                to awakening.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Sujata Stupa</strong><br />
                                A reminder of the important turning point when Sujata offered milk-rice, marking the Buddha’s shift from extreme asceticism to the
                                Middle Way.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Mahabodhi Temple Complex</strong><br />
                                The place where the Buddha attained enlightenment beneath the Bodhi Tree, one of the most sacred sites in all of Buddhism.
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold">Day 2 – December 25</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4 font-medium text-neutral-800">Rajgir – Vulture Peak – Nalanda University</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-4 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                            <li>
                                <strong>Early departure for Rajgir</strong><br />
                                A region closely connected with the period when the Buddha was actively teaching after enlightenment.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Vulture Peak (Gridhrakuta)</strong><br />
                                One of the places the Buddha often visited and taught. It is a particularly meaningful stop for meditation and Dharma reflection.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Nalanda University Ruins</strong><br />
                                A renowned center of Buddhist learning and practice that flourished for centuries, preserving a brilliant legacy of Buddhist scholarship.
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold">Day 3 – December 26</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4 font-medium text-neutral-800">Vaishali – Smriti Park – Varanasi</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-4 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                            <li>
                                <strong>Early departure for Vaishali</strong><br />
                                The place where the Buddha delivered his final discourse and also the site associated with the first ordination of Bhikkhunis.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Smriti Park</strong><br />
                                A green and peaceful space, suitable for remembrance and contemplation on the Buddha’s life, vows, and teachings.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Travel to Varanasi</strong><br />
                                Overnight stay in Varanasi.
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold">Day 4 – December 27</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4 font-medium text-neutral-800">Sarnath – Varanasi – Return to Bodh Gaya</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-4 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                            <li>
                                <strong>Sarnath</strong><br />
                                The place where the Buddha gave his first sermon after enlightenment.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Dhamek Stupa</strong><br />
                                A landmark connected with the moment when the Wheel of Dharma first began to turn, opening the path of practice for countless beings.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Optional visit to the Ganges River</strong>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Return to Bodh Gaya</strong><br />
                                End of the pilgrimage program and preparation for the main retreat.
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold">Format of the Program</h2>
                <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    This program is organized as a coordinated pilgrimage for practitioners who wish to travel together with the group before the retreat begins.
                </p>
                <ul class="mt-4 list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                    <li>A group leader will assist throughout the journey</li>
                    <li>Language support may be available in Vietnamese / English / German</li>
                    <li>During the journey, the group will mainly visit sacred sites and travel according to the shared itinerary; specific common activities will depend on actual conditions</li>
                    <li>Transportation between pilgrimage sites will be coordinated and arranged according to the practical situation</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold">Costs and Scope of Support</h2>
                <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    Participants are responsible for their own expenses, including (but not limited to):
                </p>
                <ul class="mt-4 list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                    <li>Airfare</li>
                    <li>India visa application</li>
                    <li>Accommodation</li>
                    <li>Meals</li>
                    <li>Travel to India</li>
                    <li>Entrance fees (if any)</li>
                    <li>Travel insurance (if needed)</li>
                    <li>Other personal expenses</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    However, the organizing monasteries will help coordinate, offer accommodation guidance, and assist with local arrangements when needed, so that
                    participants may join the pilgrimage more smoothly.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    Please note that this is a pilgrimage support program, not a commercial tour.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold">Participation and Preparation</h2>
                <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                    This program is suitable for practitioners who wish to join the pilgrimage before the retreat, especially those who would like additional time to
                    visit sacred sites and prepare their mind for retreat practice.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">Important notes:</p>
                <ul class="mt-4 list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 leading-7 text-neutral-700">
                    <li>The program involves a considerable amount of travel</li>
                    <li>Some days require early departures</li>
                    <li>Basic good health is required; elderly participants may still join if their health is suitable, but should carefully consider their physical condition</li>
                    <li>Participants should prepare necessary documents and personal items in advance, including passport, visa, personal medicine, suitable clothing, and daily essentials for the pilgrimage days</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
        </div>
    </section>
</Layout>